*@mweiczorek commented on Mar 11, 2020, 8:29 AM UTC:*

Same issue here. I work on the Flutter project with VS Code, but I needed to open it in Android Studio to add a library to the native side of the project, and I get this same error with Kotlin 1.3.50\. The fact that we're all getting the same errors with different versions of Kotlin would suggest the problem does not lie with Kotlin.

*@mweiczorek commented on Mar 11, 2020, 9:17 AM UTC:*

Update. The FlutterActivity implements `android.arch.lifecycle.LifecycleOwner`, but the `android.arch`package is missing from my SDK.

Another issue is that the `app/build.gradle` file specifies API version 28, but the libraries show 29
[![111](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/224439/76400060-45869d80-63b2-11ea-8ffa-08eaa19d2b8a.png)](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/224439/76400060-45869d80-63b2-11ea-8ffa-08eaa19d2b8a.png)

```
android {
    compileSdkVersion 28
    ....
    defaultConfig {
        ....
        minSdkVersion 16
        targetSdkVersion 28
        versionCode flutterVersionCode.toInteger()
        versionName flutterVersionName
        testInstrumentationRunner "androidx.test.runner.AndroidJUnitRunner"
    }
}

```

I haven't changed anything in either gradle file. All SDK's listed int eh SDK manager are labeled as 'Installed'.

This project was created in the terminal with `flutter create`. This works perfectly using the emulator via the VS Code debugger, even with the missing package.

I created a new Flutter project using Adroid Studio with the exact same result.

I've looked at [this link](https://developer.android.com/jetpack/androidx/releases/lifecycle#kotlin) regarding adding this dependency manually (even though I am not using `androidx` artifacts, the method should be the same), but any change I make to the gradle file does not result in anything being downloaded and installed. In the past, when I build a native Android app with Java, any edits made to the gradle would immediately trigger the update (as indicated by a progress indicator at the right of the application's status bar). With this, nothing happens.

I should also note that I have no gradle functionality, and I have no way to open the "Project Settings" dialog.

There are two definitions of `io.flutter.embedding.android.FlutterActivity` in external libraries:

- flutter_embedding_debug, a Gradle library downloaded from a Maven repo

For wayward souls that happened upon this, here is what worked for me:

- The fix that was referenced by @xster currently requires that you switch to the 'master' branch of Flutter. So do this:

```
$ flutter channel master
$ flutter upgrade
```

This takes you out of the 'Stable' branch of Flutter, so I'm sure there's probably some standard disclaimer about that.

After that (for good measure, not sure this part is necessary), I did the cleanup steps referenced by @phanirithvij:

1. cd flutter_installed_dir then rm -rf bin/cache/artifacts/engine/android*
2. flutter clean && flutter pub get
3. Android Studio -> Invalidate caches and restart -> Sync project with Gradle

I then re-opened Android Studio and let it reinitialize everything, and the error went away.
It worked, although changing the flutter channel for this reason does feel a bit cringey.
